   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "a739b699-50d5-4349-8fb4-a106d63fdb1a",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "# D2L Linear Algebra — Exercises 1–4 (Corrected, Rigorous)\n",
    "\n",
    "---\n",
    "\n",
    "## 1) Prove $({\\bf A}^\\top)^\\top = {\\bf A}$\n",
    "\n",
    "Let ${\\bf A}\\in\\mathbb{R}^{m\\times n}$. By the definition of transpose, for any valid indices $i,j$:\n",
    "\n",
    "- $({\\bf A}^\\top)_{ij} = A_{ji}$\n",
    "\n",
    "Transpose again:\n",
    "\n",
    "- $(({\\bf A}^\\top)^\\top)_{ij} = ({\\bf A}^\\top)_{ji} = A_{ij}$\n",
    "\n",
    "Since every entry matches, we conclude:\n",
    "- $({\\bf A}^\\top)^\\top = {\\bf A}$.\n",
    "\n",
    "**Common mistakes / reminders**\n",
    "- Saying “element-wise” without writing the index equation $((\\cdot)_{ij})$ is not a proof.\n",
    "- Confusing ${\\bf A}^\\top$ (transpose) with ${\\bf A}^{-1}$ (inverse). Totally different.\n",
    "\n",
    "---\n",
    "\n",
    "## 2) Show ${\\bf A}^\\top + {\\bf B}^\\top = ({\\bf A}+{\\bf B})^\\top$\n",
    "\n",
    "Assume ${\\bf A},{\\bf B}$ have the same shape $m\\times n$. For any $i,j$:\n",
    "\n",
    "- $(({\\bf A}+{\\bf B})^\\top)_{ij} = ({\\bf A}+{\\bf B})_{ji} = A_{ji}+B_{ji}$  \n",
    "- $( {\\bf A}^\\top + {\\bf B}^\\top )_{ij} = ({\\bf A}^\\top)_{ij} + ({\\bf B}^\\top)_{ij} = A_{ji}+B_{ji}$\n",
    "\n",
    "Thus, the two matrices have identical entries for all $i,j$, so:\n",
    "- $({\\bf A}+{\\bf B})^\\top = {\\bf A}^\\top + {\\bf B}^\\top$.\n",
    "\n",
    "**Common mistakes / reminders**\n",
    "- Forgetting the condition “same shape” for ${\\bf A}+{\\bf B}$.\n",
    "- Writing “same as Q1” without actually showing the equality.\n",
    "\n",
    "---\n",
    "\n",
    "## 3) Is ${\\bf A}+{\\bf A}^\\top$ always symmetric?\n",
    "\n",
    "Yes (for any square ${\\bf A}\\in\\mathbb{R}^{n\\times n}$).\n",
    "\n",
    "A matrix ${\\bf S}$ is symmetric iff ${\\bf S}^\\top={\\bf S}$. Let ${\\bf S}={\\bf A}+{\\bf A}^\\top$. Then:\n",
    "\n",
    "- ${\\bf S}^\\top = ({\\bf A}+{\\bf A}^\\top)^\\top$  \n",
    "- Using Q2: $({\\bf A}+{\\bf A}^\\top)^\\top = {\\bf A}^\\top + ({\\bf A}^\\top)^\\top$  \n",
    "- Using Q1: $({\\bf A}^\\top)^\\top = {\\bf A}$\n",
    "\n",
    "So:\n",
    "- ${\\bf S}^\\top = {\\bf A}^\\top + {\\bf A} = {\\bf A}+{\\bf A}^\\top = {\\bf S}$\n",
    "\n",
    "Therefore ${\\bf A}+{\\bf A}^\\top$ is symmetric.\n",
    "\n",
    "**Common mistakes / reminders**\n",
    "- This requires ${\\bf A}$ to be square so that ${\\bf A}$ and ${\\bf A}^\\top$ have the same shape and can be added.\n",
    "- “Symmetric” means equal to its transpose, not “looks mirrored” in some vague sense.\n",
    "\n",
    "---\n",
    "\n",
    "## 4) If $X$ has shape $(2,3,4)$, what is `len(X)`?\n",
    "\n",
    "`len(X)` is the size of the **first axis** (axis 0).  \n",
    "So for shape $(2,3,4)$:\n",
    "\n",
    "- $\\texttt{len}(X)=2$\n",
    "\n",
    "**Common mistakes / reminders**\n",
    "- `len(X)` is **not** the total number of elements (that would be `X.numel()` in PyTorch / `X.size` in NumPy).\n",
    "- `len(X)` is **not** the number of axes (that would be `X.ndim` / `X.dim()`).\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "a94f8588-25d6-4049-9c9d-f7a68f456014",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "## 5) For arbitrary shape, does `len(X)` correspond to which axis?\n",
    "\n",
    "Yes. For any tensor/array `X` with shape $(d_0, d_1, \\dots, d_{k-1})$:\n",
    "\n",
    "- $\\texttt{len}(X)=d_0$\n",
    "\n",
    "So `len(X)` always returns the length of **axis 0** (the first axis).\n",
    "\n",
    "**Common mistakes / reminders**\n",
    "- People often think broadcasting/shape logic is “left-aligned”; `len` is always about the **first** axis, not the last.\n",
    "- If `X` is a scalar (0-D tensor), `len(X)` is not defined (it errors).\n",
    "\n",
    "---\n",
    "\n",
    "## 6) Run `A / A.sum(axis=1)` — what happens and why?\n",
    "\n",
    "Assume (as in D2L) that `A` is a 2D tensor, e.g. shape $(2,3)$.\n",
    "\n",
    "1) Shapes:\n",
    "- $A\\in\\mathbb{R}^{2\\times 3}$\n",
    "- `A.sum(axis=1)` sums across columns, so its shape is $(2,)$  \n",
    "  (one sum per row)\n",
    "\n",
    "2) Division tries elementwise broadcasting:\n",
    "- We attempt $A \\oslash s$ where $s = A.sum(axis=1)$ has shape $(2,)$.\n",
    "\n",
    "Broadcasting aligns shapes **from the right**:\n",
    "- $A$ has shape $(2,3)$\n",
    "- $s$ has shape $(2)$, which lines up with the **last** dimension of $A$ (which is 3)\n",
    "\n",
    "Mismatch:\n",
    "- last dim: $3$ vs $2$  → cannot broadcast → runtime error.\n",
    "\n",
    "3) Correct fix (make the divisor shape $(2,1)$ so it broadcasts across columns):\n",
    "- Use `keepdims=True` so the summed axis stays as length 1:\n",
    "  - `A.sum(axis=1, keepdims=True)` has shape $(2,1)$\n",
    "- Then $(2,3)$ divided by $(2,1)$ broadcasts to $(2,3)$.\n",
    "\n",
    "Mathematically, this computes **row-normalization**:\n",
    "- Let $r_i=\\sum_{j=1}^{3}A_{ij}$\n",
    "- Output entries: $\\tilde A_{ij} = A_{ij}/r_i$\n",
    "\n",
    "**Common mistakes / reminders**\n",
    "- Broadcasting is **right-aligned**, not left-aligned.\n",
    "- In PyTorch, use `dim` not `axis` (NumPy uses `axis`). D2L sometimes abstracts this via its backend wrapper.\n",
    "- If any row sum is 0, you’ll get division-by-zero issues (inf/nan).\n",
    "\n",
    "---\n",
    "\n",
    "## 7) Manhattan travel distance (avenues/streets): can you go diagonally?\n",
    "\n",
    "In a grid city like Manhattan, you typically move only along:\n",
    "- avenues (say $x$ direction)\n",
    "- streets (say $y$ direction)\n",
    "\n",
    "So from point $(x_1,y_1)$ to $(x_2,y_2)$, the distance you must cover is:\n",
    "\n",
    "- $d_{\\text{Manhattan}} = |x_1-x_2| + |y_1-y_2|$\n",
    "\n",
    "This is the **Manhattan distance**, also called the **$L_1$ norm** distance:\n",
    "- $d = \\| (x_1-x_2,\\, y_1-y_2)\\|_1$\n",
    "\n",
    "Diagonal shortcuts (straight-line through buildings) are not allowed in the basic grid model, so you cannot “cut across” to reduce $|x_1-x_2| + |y_1-y_2|$.\n",
    "\n",
    "**Common mistakes / reminders**\n",
    "- Do not confuse with Euclidean distance (straight line):\n",
    "  - $d_{\\text{Euclid}}=\\sqrt{(x_1-x_2)^2+(y_1-y_2)^2}$\n",
    "- Manhattan distance is about constrained movement, not geometry alone.\n",
    "\n",
    "---\n",
    "\n",
    "## 8) For shape $(2,3,4)$, what are the shapes of `sum` along axes 0, 1, 2?\n",
    "\n",
    "Let $X$ have shape $(2,3,4)$.\n",
    "\n",
    "- Sum over axis 0 removes the first dimension:\n",
    "  - `X.sum(axis=0)` has shape $(3,4)$\n",
    "- Sum over axis 1 removes the second dimension:\n",
    "  - `X.sum(axis=1)` has shape $(2,4)$\n",
    "- Sum over axis 2 removes the third dimension:\n",
    "  - `X.sum(axis=2)` has shape $(2,3)$\n",
    "\n",
    "Rule: summing over axis $k$ removes dimension $k$ (unless you keep it with `keepdims=True`).\n",
    "\n",
    "**Common mistakes / reminders**\n",
    "- Axis counting starts at 0.\n",
    "- `keepdims=True` keeps the axis as size 1 (useful for broadcasting).\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "b7d861d7-6b19-4d4f-97cd-95cec9c8b24e",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "\n",
    "## 9) What does `linalg.norm` compute for tensors with 3+ axes?\n",
    "\n",
    "Default behavior (typical in NumPy / PyTorch): if you call `linalg.norm(X)` **without specifying `axis`**, it treats all entries of $X$ as one long vector and computes the Euclidean norm:\n",
    "\n",
    "- $\\|X\\|_2 = \\sqrt{\\sum_{i} X_i^2}$  \n",
    "  (where $i$ ranges over *all* elements of the tensor)\n",
    "\n",
    "So it is equivalent to flattening:\n",
    "- $\\|X\\|_2 = \\|\\text{vec}(X)\\|_2$\n",
    "\n",
    "If you specify `axis`, it computes norms along that axis (or axes), producing a tensor of norms.\n",
    "\n",
    "**Common mistakes / reminders**\n",
    "- “It always flattens” is only true for the default call; `axis` changes the meaning.\n",
    "- Different `ord` values give different norms (e.g., $L_1$, Frobenius, etc.), depending on library and arguments.\n",
    "\n",
    "---\n",
    "\n",
    "## 10) Compute ${\\bf A}{\\bf B}{\\bf C}$: is $(AB)C$ vs $A(BC)$ different?\n",
    "\n",
    "Given:\n",
    "- ${\\bf A}\\in\\mathbb{R}^{2^{10}\\times 2^{16}}$\n",
    "- ${\\bf B}\\in\\mathbb{R}^{2^{16}\\times 2^{5}}$\n",
    "- ${\\bf C}\\in\\mathbb{R}^{2^{5}\\times 2^{14}}$\n",
    "\n",
    "### Intermediate sizes (this is the key)\n",
    "1) $(AB)$ has shape:\n",
    "- $(2^{10}\\times 2^{5})$\n",
    "because $(2^{10}\\times 2^{16})(2^{16}\\times 2^{5})\\to (2^{10}\\times 2^{5})$\n",
    "\n",
    "Then $(AB)C$ multiplies:\n",
    "- $(2^{10}\\times 2^{5})(2^{5}\\times 2^{14})\\to (2^{10}\\times 2^{14})$\n",
    "\n",
    "2) $(BC)$ has shape:\n",
    "- $(2^{16}\\times 2^{14})$\n",
    "because $(2^{16}\\times 2^{5})(2^{5}\\times 2^{14})\\to (2^{16}\\times 2^{14})$\n",
    "\n",
    "Then $A(BC)$ multiplies:\n",
    "- $(2^{10}\\times 2^{16})(2^{16}\\times 2^{14})\\to (2^{10}\\times 2^{14})$\n",
    "\n",
    "### Memory footprint\n",
    "- $(AB)$ intermediate: $2^{10}\\cdot 2^{5} = 2^{15}$ entries (small)\n",
    "- $(BC)$ intermediate: $2^{16}\\cdot 2^{14} = 2^{30}$ entries (massive)\n",
    "\n",
    "So **$(AB)C$ uses dramatically less memory**.\n",
    "\n",
    "### Speed (FLOPs)\n",
    "Matrix multiply cost (roughly): $(m\\times k)(k\\times n)$ costs $O(mkn)$ multiplications.\n",
    "\n",
    "- Cost of $AB$: $2^{10}\\cdot 2^{16}\\cdot 2^{5} = 2^{31}$\n",
    "- Cost of $(AB)C$: $2^{10}\\cdot 2^{5}\\cdot 2^{14} = 2^{29}$\n",
    "- Total for $(AB)C$: $2^{31}+2^{29}$\n",
    "\n",
    "- Cost of $BC$: $2^{16}\\cdot 2^{5}\\cdot 2^{14} = 2^{35}$\n",
    "- Cost of $A(BC)$: $2^{10}\\cdot 2^{16}\\cdot 2^{14} = 2^{40}$\n",
    "- Total for $A(BC)$: $2^{35}+2^{40}$ (much larger)\n",
    "\n",
    "**Conclusion:** $(AB)C$ is both **faster** and **far smaller** in memory than $A(BC)$ here.\n",
    "\n",
    "**Common mistakes / reminders**\n",
    "- Your original intuition “do BC first” is wrong for these specific dimensions because $(BC)$ explodes in size.\n",
    "- Always compare *intermediate shapes* and *FLOPs*.\n",
    "\n",
    "---\n",
    "\n",
    "## 11) Speed: compute $AB$ or $AC^\\top$? What if $C=B^\\top$ without cloning?\n",
    "\n",
    "Given:\n",
    "- ${\\bf A}\\in\\mathbb{R}^{2^{10}\\times 2^{16}}$\n",
    "- ${\\bf B}\\in\\mathbb{R}^{2^{16}\\times 2^{5}}$\n",
    "- ${\\bf C}\\in\\mathbb{R}^{2^{5}\\times 2^{16}}$\n",
    "\n",
    "Both products $AB$ and $A C^\\top$ have the same output shape:\n",
    "- $AB$: $(2^{10}\\times 2^{16})(2^{16}\\times 2^5)\\to (2^{10}\\times 2^5)$\n",
    "- $AC^\\top$: $(2^{10}\\times 2^{16})(2^{16}\\times 2^5)\\to (2^{10}\\times 2^5)$ since $C^\\top\\in\\mathbb{R}^{2^{16}\\times 2^5}$\n",
    "\n",
    "### FLOPs\n",
    "They are the same order:\n",
    "- both cost about $2^{10}\\cdot 2^{16}\\cdot 2^5 = 2^{31}$\n",
    "\n",
    "### Why speed can still differ in practice\n",
    "Because of **memory layout / contiguity**:\n",
    "- A transposed view like $C^\\top$ may be **non-contiguous** (different strides).\n",
    "- Many fast GEMM kernels (BLAS) run best when inputs are contiguous or in preferred layouts.\n",
    "- If $C^\\top$ is non-contiguous, the library may:\n",
    "  - create a contiguous copy internally, or\n",
    "  - use a slower kernel.\n",
    "\n",
    "### If you set $C=B^\\top$ *without cloning*\n",
    "Then $C$ shares memory with $B$ (a view), so $C^\\top$ is (often) essentially $B$ again, but the **stride pattern** can still matter. Also:\n",
    "- Some operations will trigger implicit copies to get contiguous blocks.\n",
    "- Sharing memory can be good for saving RAM, but can cause surprising performance differences.\n",
    "\n",
    "**Conclusion:** numerical values do not determine speed; **layout and contiguity** do.\n",
    "\n",
    "**Common mistakes / reminders**\n",
    "- “B and C have different numbers so speed differs” — false.\n",
    "- The main issue is *strides/cache/BLAS kernels*, not math.\n",
    "\n",
    "---\n",
    "\n",
    "## 12) Stack ${\\bf A},{\\bf B},{\\bf C}\\in\\mathbb{R}^{100\\times 200}$ into a 3-axis tensor; recover ${\\bf B}$\n",
    "\n",
    "If you use a standard stack (e.g., `stack([A,B,C])`), it creates a new leading axis:\n",
    "\n",
    "- Shape becomes $(3,100,200)$\n",
    "\n",
    "Index meaning:\n",
    "- axis 0 selects which matrix: 0→$A$, 1→$B$, 2→$C$\n",
    "\n",
    "To recover ${\\bf B}$:\n",
    "- slice index 1 on axis 0:\n",
    "  - $X[1,:,:]$ has shape $(100,200)$ and equals ${\\bf B}$.\n",
    "\n",
    "If instead you stack along a new last axis (conceptually “put them side-by-side in a third axis”), you can get:\n",
    "- shape $(100,200,3)$\n",
    "and then ${\\bf B}$ is:\n",
    "- $X[:,:,1]$\n",
    "\n",
    "**Common mistakes / reminders**\n",
    "- Default stack usually makes shape $(3,100,200)$, not $(100,200,3)$.\n",
    "- Mixing up `stack` vs `concatenate`: concatenate does not create a new axis; stack does.\n"
   ]
  },
